College Admissions Visualization

JF Schultz

2023-01-16

Introduction

The project began with a preliminary data set which included the number of applicants and admissions to US colleges and university, i.e examining college admission rates. The goal was to develop a visualization to represent the distribution of the admission rates of applicants across the US and amomig the various schools. The task for the user is to recognize the pattern in admission rates and identify individual schools of a desired admission rate. To address that task, the key elements to represent included: the number of applicants, acceptance rate, and size (enrollment). Intended users included those with a general interest in admission rates such as applicants, those assisting them (parents, counselors), or as part of a general social study or background.

Additional data was added to deliver more information and knowledge about acceptance rates. Admission rate data was combined with data for standardized test scores of applicants correponding with the same applicant pool.

An initial visualization was created with specific key elements. A plot of the relationship of applicants to admissions was used as a graphical representation of the admission rate. Detail information was demonstrated by an interactive feature with hovering. As a user hovers the cursor over and individual point, the following information is identified: Name, Admission Rate, standardized test scores. The standardized test scores were represented on a visual bar scale for more intuitive interpretation. Due to the large number of data points, an interactive feature was included to enable users to zoom and pan through particular ranges of interest. At extremes and as admission rates diverge, it becomes more difficult to intuitively recognize a school’s admission rate. A color scale indicator was added in order to more intuitively identify an individual school’s admission rate.

Data

The dataset is compiled from The Integrated Postsecondary Education Data System (IPEDS) landing page

IPEDS (Integrated Postsecondary Education Data System) is an annual data collection distributed by the Postsecondary Branch of the National Center for Education Statistics (NCES), a non-partisan center of the Institute of Education Sciences under the U.S. Department of Education. NCES is the primary federal entity for collecting and analyzing data related to education in the U.S. and other nations.

Selection Criteria
Of the 6,289 institutions listed with IPEDS, institutions which offer a four-year program conferring an undergraduate degree were included (n = 2,556). Dataset was limited to institutions reporting numbers for both number of applicants and admissions, and enrollment size greater than 100 (n = 1,386).

Evaluation

In order to evaluate the visualization, a think-aloud and semi-structured interview process was used to determine its effectiveness. Representative participants were selected and permitted to freely explore the visualization. Participants’ voiced observations were noted. Particular interest was noted on ease of usability, depth of insight, and accuracy. A post utilization semi-structured interview was performed to better understand insights, intuitiveness of use, difficulties, and deficiencies in either visualization or information.

The visualization was reviewed by three individuals:

  • SCH, 47 year old mother of two college age children (an undergraduate senior at CU Boulder, and an undergraduate freshman attending community college anticipating transfer to a 4-year institution) and with BS, MSN, and DNP degrees in Nursing
  • AL, 29 year old fellow student in CU MSDS program with knowledge in Data Visualization techniques
  • RT, 40 year old father of two (11 and 8 years old) with undergraduate and advanced degrees, technologically skilled and employed in an IT related field

Summary of Evaluations:

  • with initial view, without zooming, the data appears very dense
  • availability of zoom / pan controls was not readily apparent initially
  • with zoom / pan controls, the amount of information represented, i.e. the number and variety of schools was more than expected, and impressive
  • discovered that admission scores data populate by exploring main visualization with hovering
  • generated new insight - identified schools with exclusive, i.e. low admission rates previously not aware of, e.g. Minerva University (admission rate 0.01)
  • generated new insight - size of institution is not necessarily related to admission rate, i.e. a large school doesn’t necesarily have a low(er) admission rate
  • generated new insight - a large number of institutions with very high admission rates across a wide spectrum of school sizes
  • generated new insight - a much smaller (relative) number of schools with low(er) admission rates with a large spread across admission rates and school sizes
  • visualization of point position on x, y coordinates made it easier to identify schools with high admission rates
  • interpretation of admission rates which fell away from main line and grouping was much easier given the color scale
  • individual institution details (name, admission rate) with hovering was very helpful to identify admission rate without having to try to estimate from x, y coordinates
  • visualization generated additional interest in exploring relationship between institutions, admission rates, and test scores, particularly with interest in developing a new visualization of the “reverse” i.e. starting with test scores and visualizing resultant schools with anticipated admissions

Conclusion and Discussion

The visualization was effective and informative in conveying the main objective of demonstrating the distribution of college admission rates. Specific key elements were notably successful: an x, y scale rather than just the admission / acceptance rate, was helpful and provided an additional dimension of information and understanding of school size; color scale for admission rates, rather than just x, y coordinates made interpretation much more intuitive; additional information of test scores added another dimension of understanding. Specific drawbacks were noted and could be easily overcome in further iterations: availability of zoom / pan controls; and availability of score data from hovering. While these were minor issues which were quickly self-resolved by users once they began to explore the visualization, these issues could be avoided with minimal informational instructions. Certain users potentially might not discover the controls on their own and expect the visualization to be static which would greatly reduce its functionality and the amount of information conveyed. A small insert legend noting control options would encourage more user interaction and likely reduce lag time to discover the options.

User testing and Evaluation demonstrated immediate user interest and new insight depth. Notably, all three test users expressed some interest in further visualizations and features not due to deficiencies but in interest of gaining further insight. This speaks to the effectiveness of the visualization to engage users, generate new insight, and develop interest.
